		<description><![CDATA[Here&#8217;s the one problem that I see given the constraints of the hardware with respect to the SMS.app:  You can send texts to multiple &#8230;]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Here&#8217;s the one problem that I see given the constraints of the hardware with respect to the SMS.app:  You can send texts to multiple people, but the problem is, when someone replies, it goes into a separate text&#8230;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>The Problem:</strong></p>
<div class="problem">
<div class="problemContent"><img class="size-full wp-image-438" title="p_480_320_17D42618-32F1-4F03-9858-68C45491AFA0.jpeg" src="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/p_480_320_17D42618-32F1-4F03-9858-68C45491AFA0.jpeg" alt="" width="192" height="288" /><br />
<img class="size-full wp-image-440" title="p_480_320_B534019A-D516-4B54-8E93-FB10083E60A4.jpeg" src="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/p_480_320_B534019A-D516-4B54-8E93-FB10083E60A4-e1264643073500.jpeg" alt="" width="191" height="115" /></p>
<div class="text">Notice how the text initially sent to two people gets split into separate texts with a response.  It&#8217;s a fair implementation, but assumes the user doesn&#8217;t want to carry on a conversation with multiple contacts.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>What I would like to see are 2 simple features that would allow for a more versatile texting experience.</p>
<ul>
<li>as the sender, I would like to be able to choose to thread the conversations</li>
<li>as the recipient of a threaded message, I&#8217;d like the option to remove myself from said conversation at any time.</li>
</ul>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>The Solution:</strong></p>
<div class="solution">
<div class="solutionContent"><a href="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/sms.jpeg"><img class="size-full wp-image-474 alignnone" title="sms" src="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/sms.jpeg" alt="" width="183" height="275" /></a><br />
<a href="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/response.jpeg"><img class="size-full wp-image-473 alignnone" title="response" src="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/response.jpeg" alt="" width="181" height="74" /></a></p>
<p>It would then be left up to the good people of Apple&#8217;s UI department to decide how to display the alert in the text box in a non-annoying way (and to provide a choice to /not to receive the rest of the threads) and for the engineers at Apple to manage how recipients can individually choose to unsubscribe from a text thread.  Minor details.</p>
</div>
</div>
<p>All in all, the iPhone really changed the purpose of txt messaging, transforming it into a psuedo-chat experience on the iPhone.  Why not complete the conversion by making group texting easier.  Sure it might get annoying, but in that case just slap a setting in the Settings.app under SMS where people can choose to never recieve replies from threaded txts.  I think it&#8217;d be a sweet feature.  On a side note&#8230; the iPad?!? Really?.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
